{"type":"WRoot","isHeaderIncluded":true,"areCommentsAvailable":false,"headerTitleAlign":"center","headerTitleColor":"#000000ff","headerImageSrc":"http://localhost/savora/fs/file/7c4f315b245cb555bd0b502d29ad1485c5edd02fb40d54d4a5e36f634b8dac88?v=img%3Afull-hd","headerImageHash":"7c4f315b245cb555bd0b502d29ad1485c5edd02fb40d54d4a5e36f634b8dac88","headerImageVariant":"img:full-hd","children":[{"type":"WText","textEditor":{"type":"WTextEditor","content":[["Cooking tips"]],"mode":"simple"}},{"type":"WText","textEditor":{"type":"WTextEditor","content":[["Good cooking isn’t about memorizing recipes — it’s about controlling variables. Once you understand that, most dishes stop being guesswork. "],[],[" Start with heat. Most people misuse it. High heat isn’t “better,” it’s just faster and easier to mess up. Use high heat for searing, not for cooking everything. If food burns on the outside and stays raw inside, that’s not bad luck — that’s poor heat control. "],[],["Salt matters more than people think. Under-seasoned food tastes flat no matter how well it’s cooked. Season early, taste often, and adjust gradually. Dumping salt at the end rarely fixes anything properly."],[],["Cut ingredients consistently. Uneven sizes mean uneven cooking. If half your vegetables are tiny and the other half are large chunks, you’re forcing the pan to do two incompatible things at once. "],[],[" Don’t overcrowd the pan. When you do, you’re steaming instead of cooking. Moisture has nowhere to go, and you lose texture. Cook in batches if necessary — it’s slower, but the result is actually worth eating. "],[],[]],"mode":"simple"}},{"type":"WAi","prompt":"Can you generate static HTML table with common cooking skills if what level of cooks use the skill (the levels are novice, skilled, pro)\n\nOnly style the borders and style the header using bolder text. Do not use background color","html":"<table>\n    <tr>\n        <th>Cooking Skill</th>\n        <th>Novice</th>\n        <th>Skilled</th>\n        